00:09:56,397 --> 00:10:01,105
So we set up pre-production for every project the same way, whether it's a giant AAA game

154
00:10:01,365 --> 00:10:03,028
or a tiny two-man indie game.

155
00:10:04,031 --> 00:10:07,113
So these are kind of the concepts and the rules I follow.

156
00:10:07,133 --> 00:10:11,617
So firstly, pre-production is the most important phase for audio.

157
00:10:11,757 --> 00:10:16,561
It's your chance to build every system, to test and refine every workflow,

158
00:10:16,581 --> 00:10:19,723
because once you get into production, you're going to be running through this workflow

159
00:10:19,863 --> 00:10:21,945
over and over hundreds or thousands of times,

160
00:10:22,005 --> 00:10:24,947
and any sort of clicks you can get out of that workflow

161
00:10:24,967 --> 00:10:30,091
are going to save you loads of production time that you can spend on improving the quality.

162
00:10:31,365 --> 00:10:34,988
It's a great time to take all your creative risks and fail while it's cheap.

163
00:10:36,308 --> 00:10:38,370
And do all your creative experimentation.

164
00:10:38,410 --> 00:10:42,612
Try things out that may or may not work and set your direction.

165
00:10:43,132 --> 00:10:49,556
So this is super key in AAA games and just as important in little tiny indie games.

166
00:10:49,576 --> 00:10:55,720
I'll also say align your audio pre-production with the project pre-production.

167
00:10:56,020 --> 00:10:58,522
Now this tends to happen anyway, but just in case it doesn't,

168
00:10:59,062 --> 00:11:00,023
make sure that your...

