240
00:16:08,149 --> 00:16:12,530
can handle implementation if need be, if for some reason I'm not the one that's going to

241
00:16:12,570 --> 00:16:12,991
be doing it.

242
00:16:15,255 --> 00:16:24,742
And it means that when the time comes that everything is implemented, the same document that has now been making its way through the entire project can be handed to QA.

243
00:16:25,423 --> 00:16:30,186
And I don't have to be the only person who knows how music is supposed to function throughout the game.

244
00:16:30,626 --> 00:16:37,531
It's all detailed there and QA can go through and see what's not working as designed and what is working correctly.

245
00:16:41,157 --> 00:16:43,697
So let's take a step back for a second and think about

246
00:16:43,757 --> 00:16:44,617
classic pinball.

247
00:16:44,737 --> 00:16:48,658
So classic pinball has two main acoustic elements.

248
00:16:48,918 --> 00:16:51,719
You've got the mechanical and physical sounds of the actual

249
00:16:51,779 --> 00:16:55,020
table, and you've got the additional sound effects and

250
00:16:55,060 --> 00:16:57,560
music layers to add excitement and reward to that.

251
00:16:57,640 --> 00:17:01,741
So if you think about it from a UX point of view, for the UX

252
00:17:02,602 --> 00:17:05,022
of pinball audio, the goals are kind of like this.

253
00:17:05,702 --> 00:17:09,103
To make short play time really exciting, to give you

254
00:17:09,203 --> 00:17:10,823
immediate visceral feedback.

255
00:17:11,584 --> 00:17:15,526
to be really rewarding, and lastly to help the player know what to do.

256
00:17:16,847 --> 00:17:22,930
So for Yoku's Island Express, which is, it was inherently organic with a lot of soft surfaces,

257
00:17:23,010 --> 00:17:26,452
so it made some of the immediate physical feedback a little bit harder.

258
00:17:27,072 --> 00:17:33,095
You know, the surfaces are dirt, grass, snow, and with Yoku being a dung beetle,

259
00:17:33,135 --> 00:17:34,636
the ball is made of, well...

260
00:17:37,897 --> 00:17:51,984
So, anyway, the reward sounds needed to be a lot gentler, because the longer playtime

261
00:17:52,184 --> 00:17:57,887
and the creative style of the world, so we were trying to give a calmer overall feel,

262
00:17:58,367 --> 00:17:59,668
which meant less intense sounds.

263
00:18:00,931 --> 00:18:03,352
And a lot of the reward sounds only use C and G,

264
00:18:03,372 --> 00:18:06,633
because I was trying to avoid dissonance with the music.

265
00:18:06,653 --> 00:18:09,134
And I actually asked Jesse to write all the music

266
00:18:09,174 --> 00:18:12,114
in the same key to make sure that there was no dissonance,

267
00:18:12,215 --> 00:18:14,735
which worked great for the first year or so

268
00:18:14,795 --> 00:18:16,616
until Jesse forgot that we were doing that.

269
00:18:16,696 --> 00:18:16,836
Right.

270
00:18:16,856 --> 00:18:17,056
Yeah.

271
00:18:19,980 --> 00:18:22,601
It's a problem when the game goes on for three years.

272
00:18:22,741 --> 00:18:22,981
Yeah.

273
00:18:23,581 --> 00:18:27,843
So we actually got away with it in the end, but hey, whatever.

274
00:18:29,563 --> 00:18:33,364
So the character voices were one of the biggest sound design challenges for the project.

275
00:18:33,544 --> 00:18:38,665
We had no budget for VO or localization, so we had to take a lot more creative approach.

276
00:18:39,586 --> 00:18:43,847
Now I spent a lot of years at LucasArts studying Ben Burtt's sound design, which has a very

277
00:18:43,967 --> 00:18:45,147
vocal quality to it.

278
00:18:46,324 --> 00:18:52,413
A lot of the sounds used human vocal articulation, like the alien and the robot voices.

279
00:18:52,814 --> 00:18:55,498
They followed the human speech pitch patterns.

280
00:18:56,039 --> 00:19:00,926
And they were constructed using heavy editing of great source rather than heavy processing.

281
00:19:01,627 --> 00:19:04,009
So for the characters of Mokumana Island,

282
00:19:04,550 --> 00:19:08,974
I looked for animal sounds that had those same sort of human speech pitch elements

283
00:19:09,574 --> 00:19:14,639
and edited those together, and I did impressions of those sounds and mixed them together.

284
00:19:15,119 --> 00:19:17,421
So you got some animals that were a mixture,

285
00:19:17,942 --> 00:19:22,405
some that were all animals, and some were just all my voice.

286
00:19:23,126 --> 00:19:24,767
So, you know, here are some of the characters.

287
00:19:24,787 --> 00:19:26,647
You had, like, the parrot.

288
00:19:26,667 --> 00:19:27,648
That was pretty straightforward.

289
00:19:27,668 --> 00:19:31,109
I could imagine how to edit parrot sounds into that.

290
00:19:31,569 --> 00:19:32,970
You had more complicated ones,

291
00:19:33,050 --> 00:19:35,551
like a giant eel and a pterodactyl.

292
00:19:35,671 --> 00:19:38,652
That was a little more work creatively.

293
00:19:39,133 --> 00:19:40,593
And then I wasn't exactly sure what to do

294
00:19:40,653 --> 00:19:42,294
with a giant talking mushroom

295
00:19:42,334 --> 00:19:43,494
and a yellow blob with a hat.

296
00:19:44,075 --> 00:19:45,855
But, anyway, all in all,

297
00:19:46,055 --> 00:19:47,856
I was just trying to make the developers laugh.

298
00:19:47,956 --> 00:19:49,417
So here's a quick video,

299
00:19:49,957 --> 00:19:51,498
and you can decide whether I was successful.

