00:20:03,180 --> 00:20:11,584
Like and Subscribe for more Game Theory content!

301
00:20:32,844 --> 00:20:39,310
There you go.

302
00:20:39,330 --> 00:20:40,991
Thank you.

303
00:20:44,254 --> 00:20:46,196
So, about some of the other sounds.

304
00:20:46,356 --> 00:20:47,797
So the physics sounds were...

305
00:20:48,731 --> 00:20:53,293
Pretty challenging as I was saying the creative director and who's called Matthias and I and

306
00:20:53,793 --> 00:20:55,834
realized that we had to take a much more organic approach.

307
00:20:56,494 --> 00:21:01,496
So in order to match the world I went out and I bought a cricket ball and a giant marble

308
00:21:01,856 --> 00:21:06,478
and I went out to the local nature reserve and chucked it at stuff and got weird looks

309
00:21:06,498 --> 00:21:07,178
from passersby.

310
00:21:08,379 --> 00:21:14,803
And I also bought a load of children's toys and cut them apart and, you know, made weird

311
00:21:14,823 --> 00:21:18,145
sounds with them, much to the dismay of my son, who was three at the time.

312
00:21:20,127 --> 00:21:21,267
And oops.

313
00:21:21,407 --> 00:21:21,628
Yes.

314
00:21:22,368 --> 00:21:23,589
And we had...

315
00:21:24,069 --> 00:21:28,430
some metal rails which I grabbed the rack out of my oven and rolled the marble along it and

316
00:21:29,250 --> 00:21:32,571
also did a bunch of synth programming which I wasn't expecting to do.

317
00:21:33,091 --> 00:21:38,693
Some of the voices were actually came out of synths, partly for saving time and partly just

318
00:21:38,713 --> 00:21:43,294
because creatively I just wanted to come out with something totally different.

319
00:21:44,294 --> 00:21:46,535
So, musical motivation.

320
00:21:47,715 --> 00:21:51,216
When I got on the project Villa Gorilla said to me,

321
00:21:52,256 --> 00:21:53,097
just do whatever you want.

322
00:21:54,465 --> 00:21:58,874
And that's the first time in 20 years that anyone has said that to me in game development.

323
00:21:59,215 --> 00:22:03,383
And I was like, oh my god, that's amazing, the shackles are off, what am I going to do?

324
00:22:05,744 --> 00:22:06,985
And I had no idea.

325
00:22:08,026 --> 00:22:09,408
Totally awful experience.

326
00:22:10,449 --> 00:22:13,231
That's not how AAA works.

327
00:22:13,472 --> 00:22:16,555
I've had 20 years of having walked into meetings and

328
00:22:16,595 --> 00:22:18,797
people say, this is what we want it to sound like, and

329
00:22:18,817 --> 00:22:20,959
here's some YouTube videos, and here's somebody else's

330
00:22:20,979 --> 00:22:24,923
soundtrack, and please go ahead and give us what sort

331
00:22:24,963 --> 00:22:25,764
of exists already.

332
00:22:26,878 --> 00:22:29,419
So I had no idea where to even begin.

333
00:22:29,439 --> 00:22:33,242
This was one of the biggest creative challenges I faced on the entire score.

334
00:22:33,862 --> 00:22:41,826
So I decided to kind of almost zen-like go back to square one, see what was it that made

335
00:22:41,886 --> 00:22:43,908
me want to be a composer in the first place.

336
00:22:44,428 --> 00:22:49,091
I took a look at all these different scores and all these different albums and all these

337
00:22:49,131 --> 00:22:50,972
different, like, NES games.

338
00:22:52,212 --> 00:22:59,514
Everything, the melody writing of the Beatles, the production work of Mass Effect, Massive

339
00:22:59,554 --> 00:23:08,457
Attack, the current production techniques of remix artists like Pogo, all of these things

340
00:23:08,597 --> 00:23:13,018
influenced me and ended up one way or another in the game's score.

341
00:23:14,585 --> 00:23:17,527
I had a number of goals that I set for myself

342
00:23:18,167 --> 00:23:19,568
with the music score for Yoku.

343
00:23:20,288 --> 00:23:23,110
The first one was that it needed to service the game.

344
00:23:24,771 --> 00:23:28,413
As with a AAA project, I knew the music needed to,

345
00:23:28,533 --> 00:23:31,135
first and foremost, serve the needs of the game.

346
00:23:31,635 --> 00:23:34,657
So, do whatever you want isn't quite as self-indulgent as it sounds.

347
00:23:35,817 --> 00:23:36,718
It had to...

348
00:23:37,638 --> 00:23:40,440
It had a function, and that function was to support the game.

349
00:23:41,261 --> 00:23:45,505
If I make a score that supports the game, I make the developer happy.

350
00:23:46,005 --> 00:23:50,169
If I create something that gets called out in reviews, I make the developer happy.

351
00:23:50,370 --> 00:23:57,056
If I create a soundtrack that people want to listen to on Spotify and buy, I make the developer happy.

352
00:23:57,096 --> 00:23:57,937
So that was another goal.

353
00:23:59,923 --> 00:24:06,205
The harder goals for this project, one of them is something I'm calling the dichotomy

354
00:24:06,225 --> 00:24:06,925
of opposites.

355
00:24:07,425 --> 00:24:13,186
Yokozayn Express by its design is a Metroidvania mixed with a pinball game.

356
00:24:13,726 --> 00:24:18,387
And it's like chocolate and pepperoni, but somehow it works.

357
00:24:19,167 --> 00:24:20,487
And it works really beautifully.

358
00:24:21,427 --> 00:24:25,908
So I knew I wanted to reflect that musically throughout the game's entire score.

359
00:24:26,768 --> 00:24:28,428
And I'll get to that in a moment.

360
00:24:30,824 --> 00:24:34,186
And I also wanted to find, much like Tom wanted to,

361
00:24:34,386 --> 00:24:36,847
one of his goals was just to make the developers laugh,

362
00:24:37,047 --> 00:24:39,709
I also wanted to just have fun with this score,

363
00:24:39,729 --> 00:24:41,710
because there was so much creativity already.

364
00:24:42,290 --> 00:24:44,472
I wanted to see, how crazy can I take it?

365
00:24:44,512 --> 00:24:47,714
Where's the boundary where I've gone off the deep end,

366
00:24:47,974 --> 00:24:51,116
and the developers are like, that's, okay,

367
00:24:51,376 --> 00:24:53,157
like all the other stuff was fine,

368
00:24:53,197 --> 00:24:54,318
but now you've gone too far,

369
00:24:54,798 --> 00:24:56,879
and that's just nuts and doesn't fit in our game.

370
00:24:57,419 --> 00:24:59,881
And then I could walk it back and know where the boundary is.

371
00:25:01,816 --> 00:25:03,757
So let's talk about the dichotomy of opposites.

372
00:25:06,738 --> 00:25:10,059
Take for instance the opening area of the game.

373
00:25:10,119 --> 00:25:12,320
It's a nice, sweet, tropical beach.

374
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:17,842
I knew I wanted to start with some ukulele, but because I wanted to have the opposite

375
00:25:17,922 --> 00:25:23,764
of ukulele, I also thought, why not mix that with turntableism and beatboxing?

376
00:25:25,044 --> 00:25:25,784
And that led to this.

377
00:25:46,662 --> 00:25:48,444
I was thrilled with that.

378
00:25:48,564 --> 00:25:48,905
Thanks.

379
00:25:49,225 --> 00:25:49,585
Thanks.

380
00:25:49,605 --> 00:25:49,765
Thanks.

381
00:25:49,785 --> 00:25:50,286
Thanks.

382
00:25:50,306 --> 00:25:50,506
Thanks.

383
00:25:50,606 --> 00:25:50,967
Thanks.

384
00:25:50,987 --> 00:25:51,127
Thanks.

385
00:26:11,025 --> 00:26:13,026
It hit everything I wanted it to hit.

386
00:26:13,206 --> 00:26:17,408
It was two things that really don't go together usually,

387
00:26:17,568 --> 00:26:20,889
but they seemed like they'd just kind of always been waiting

388
00:26:20,929 --> 00:26:22,209
to be put together like that.

389
00:26:23,010 --> 00:26:24,970
And it was happy, and it was bright,

390
00:26:25,050 --> 00:26:28,112
and it was a great introductory way to get into the game.

391
00:26:29,179 --> 00:26:36,081
And another part in the game, there are these frogs who are monks, and they're building

392
00:26:36,221 --> 00:26:40,423
a spaceship out of wood in order to leave the planet.

393
00:26:41,984 --> 00:26:44,125
So there's this, again, this dichotomy.

394
00:26:44,145 --> 00:26:47,066
There's the science element, there's this very organic element.

395
00:26:47,406 --> 00:26:51,588
And I knew that I wanted to reflect that in the music, so I thought, well, what if I take

396
00:26:51,868 --> 00:26:52,028
the...

397
00:26:53,349 --> 00:27:01,091
The early 80s synth sounds that you'd get on like a elementary school science film strip.

398
00:27:01,571 --> 00:27:04,492
And why don't I mix that with Tuvan throat singing?

399
00:27:05,732 --> 00:27:07,773
And I did, and it sounds like this.

400
00:27:48,831 --> 00:27:50,732
So again, I was really happy with how that turned out.

401
00:27:51,953 --> 00:27:52,233
Thanks.

402
00:27:53,854 --> 00:27:56,216
And you might have heard in the background, there's a

403
00:27:56,316 --> 00:27:59,818
vocal track going C-A-T-C-C-A-T-G.

404
00:28:01,459 --> 00:28:04,521
Well, when I started the track, one of my ideas was to

405
00:28:04,601 --> 00:28:08,124
have a Gregorian chant in the track.

406
00:28:08,664 --> 00:28:12,426
But instead of having them singing liturgical text, I

407
00:28:12,446 --> 00:28:14,428
wanted them to be singing chemical formula.

408
00:28:15,944 --> 00:28:18,787
Deoxyribonucleic acid.

409
00:28:19,267 --> 00:28:19,747
That kind of thing.

410
00:28:21,629 --> 00:28:23,711
And I recorded it, and I put it in the track,

411
00:28:23,972 --> 00:28:25,073
and it sounded terrible.

412
00:28:25,313 --> 00:28:26,554
Just totally didn't work.

413
00:28:27,956 --> 00:28:28,777
Maybe that was me.

414
00:28:29,097 --> 00:28:31,499
Maybe one of you could be successful with that idea.

415
00:28:32,620 --> 00:28:33,541
Feel free to run with it.

416
00:28:35,312 --> 00:28:38,035
But I knew I still wanted something to represent that.

417
00:28:38,135 --> 00:28:40,597
So I decided, oh, well, what if I

418
00:28:40,637 --> 00:28:42,940
were to take the DNA sequence of something

419
00:28:43,440 --> 00:28:46,063
and speak it through a vocoder and just run

420
00:28:46,103 --> 00:28:47,825
that in the background of the whole track

421
00:28:48,525 --> 00:28:49,546
as almost a vocal.

422
00:28:50,367 --> 00:28:55,831
So, I did a quick Google search and the first thing I looked for was frogs, because of the

423
00:28:56,111 --> 00:28:58,053
frog monks, but I couldn't find frogs.

424
00:28:58,113 --> 00:29:00,795
But the first thing I did find was the DNA sequence of yeast.

425
00:29:01,295 --> 00:29:03,177
So thank you Google.

426
00:29:03,417 --> 00:29:07,600
I put the DNA sequence of yeast throughout the entirety of that track, just spoken in

427
00:29:07,620 --> 00:29:08,941
the background through vocoder.

428
00:29:09,582 --> 00:29:09,982
And it works.

429
00:29:12,560 --> 00:29:15,301
So how did I do with my musical goals for the score?

430
00:29:15,461 --> 00:29:16,642
Well, I serviced the game.

431
00:29:17,082 --> 00:29:19,983
The reviews frequently call out the soundtrack

432
00:29:20,183 --> 00:29:23,004
as helping with the atmosphere of the game.

433
00:29:23,824 --> 00:29:28,386
It made a number of best of lists.

434
00:29:28,406 --> 00:29:29,887
It got called out a bunch on Twitter.

435
00:29:29,987 --> 00:29:30,767
So that was great.

436
00:29:31,507 --> 00:29:32,988
Villa Gorilla was very happy with it.

437
00:29:33,028 --> 00:29:34,908
They loved using it all over their marketing stuff.

438
00:29:37,066 --> 00:29:40,407
The harder stuff, did I do this dichotomy of opposites thing?

439
00:29:40,467 --> 00:29:40,728
Yes.

440
00:29:41,128 --> 00:29:41,828
I figured that out.

441
00:29:41,888 --> 00:29:43,009
I was very happy with it.

442
00:29:43,849 --> 00:29:49,751
Now I got to a point where I thought, all right, this track is the one they're going

443
00:29:49,771 --> 00:29:50,332
to shoot down.

444
00:29:51,952 --> 00:30:00,896
I had written a track that was a medieval fugue for sham and crumhorn and bebop saxophone,

445
00:30:01,536 --> 00:30:04,418
and after about 30 seconds of that, it became a reggae track.

446
00:30:06,411 --> 00:30:08,112
And I said, here?

447
00:30:08,132 --> 00:30:11,074
And gave it to the devs and they were like, yeah, cool, great, this sounds good.

448
00:30:11,675 --> 00:30:17,199
So I never found a place where I managed to go too far.

449
00:30:17,219 --> 00:30:20,822
I never found where they were like, no, that's too nuts.

450
00:30:21,042 --> 00:30:29,209
So I think trying to push myself to find that, I don't think I normally would have gone for

451
00:30:30,510 --> 00:30:32,191
medieval reggae bebop.

452
00:30:33,132 --> 00:30:34,433
But I got there.

453
00:30:35,441 --> 00:30:36,746
Okay, so technical challenges.

454
00:30:37,970 --> 00:30:38,312
All right.

455
00:30:39,683 --> 00:30:41,024
So technical tribulations.

456
00:30:41,064 --> 00:30:43,425
Let's start with middleware.

457
00:30:43,445 --> 00:30:45,426
So I mentioned at the start of the talk

458
00:30:45,486 --> 00:30:49,989
that the team was a bit skeptical about getting Wwise

459
00:30:50,029 --> 00:30:52,510
into the workflow because it was expensive

460
00:30:53,071 --> 00:30:57,133
and it gave them not very much control over the audio code.

461
00:30:57,693 --> 00:30:58,914
So I had to make a case for it.

462
00:30:59,714 --> 00:31:01,355
And making a case for middleware is

463
00:31:01,375 --> 00:31:03,997
something I've done a number of times over a number of games

464
00:31:04,097 --> 00:31:04,937
with some success.

465
00:31:04,997 --> 00:31:07,159
So here's how I approach it.

466
00:31:08,059 --> 00:31:14,142
So firstly, when I make my case, I come up with a feature list of all the things we'll need from the middleware for the game,

467
00:31:14,902 --> 00:31:18,424
and then work out the cost of making that themselves, or ourselves.

468
00:31:19,144 --> 00:31:20,925
And usually it kind of works out like this.

469
00:31:21,726 --> 00:31:29,009
It's cheaper to do it ourselves, which doesn't seem that obvious, and then the team says, well, why do it?

470
00:31:29,269 --> 00:31:30,930
Well, there are other elements too.

471
00:31:31,550 --> 00:31:32,371
So debugging.

472
00:31:33,051 --> 00:31:46,682
Yes, you can make it yourself, but when you add the time you're going to spend debugging, it gets more expensive, and to get it to the same level of quality and reliability as middleware, it sort of works out about even, but it doesn't end there.

473
00:31:47,666 --> 00:31:51,529
You've got iteration time to worry about, like how quick is it to get your assets in

474
00:31:51,569 --> 00:31:57,212
there and then iterate on it and get it to the level of quality that you want, and that

475
00:31:57,353 --> 00:31:59,254
increases the cost as well.

476
00:31:59,294 --> 00:32:03,837
And then if you want to make it scale, so it's all very well making it work for just

477
00:32:03,897 --> 00:32:08,080
a few assets, but then what if you're dealing with thousands of assets or tens of thousands

478
00:32:08,120 --> 00:32:08,600
of assets?

479
00:32:09,141 --> 00:32:12,523
If your system's going to need more work to make it scale, it sort of ends up here, and

480
00:32:12,543 --> 00:32:12,683
then...

481
00:32:13,443 --> 00:32:15,544
You know, the independence of the audio workflow.

482
00:32:15,844 --> 00:32:18,345
Are you going to be sharing the same files when you're working?

483
00:32:18,765 --> 00:32:21,586
Working with Wwise means I don't need to have those files checked out.

484
00:32:21,906 --> 00:32:26,067
And it, you know, ended up kind of off the charts and the team were like,

485
00:32:26,147 --> 00:32:28,008
OK, fine, we'll just use Wwise.

486
00:32:28,668 --> 00:32:31,448
So, music tech.

487
00:32:31,588 --> 00:32:31,769
Yes.

488
00:32:33,409 --> 00:32:40,291
I had the task of figuring out what is the interactive music functionality of the game going to be.

489
00:32:41,708 --> 00:32:43,548
How granular did I want it to be?

490
00:32:43,588 --> 00:32:46,309
And I had some really high concept ideas I wanted to try.

491
00:32:46,329 --> 00:32:49,690
I wanted music that adapted as you solved puzzles.

492
00:32:50,470 --> 00:32:54,771
Maybe the instrumentation changed as you completed a puzzle.

493
00:32:55,431 --> 00:32:59,672
The team asked me, they said there's a central hub village in the game.

494
00:32:59,712 --> 00:33:03,173
And they said that as you complete parts of the game, maybe as you come back

495
00:33:03,213 --> 00:33:06,034
to the hub, there's new layers of music.

496
00:33:06,994 --> 00:33:10,275
And the track builds up the more you complete of the game.

497
00:33:11,595 --> 00:33:17,599
And one of the things I really wanted to try was boss music that changed tonality when you scored a hit on the boss.

498
00:33:17,679 --> 00:33:28,425
So, hit the boss, all of a sudden this minor key track switches to major for a few bars and then seamlessly switches back into minor.

499
00:33:28,666 --> 00:33:32,048
And I had some prototypes that I made and it was working really beautifully.

500
00:33:32,788 --> 00:33:34,229
Unfortunately, I had low time.

501
00:33:36,935 --> 00:33:38,996
Because the game was only supposed to take one year,

502
00:33:39,596 --> 00:33:43,338
and because I'm freelancing, I have to go out and find jobs.

503
00:33:43,899 --> 00:33:46,380
And as is so frequently the case with freelancing,

504
00:33:47,060 --> 00:33:48,101
everything hit at once.

505
00:33:48,581 --> 00:33:51,963
And by the time it was deep in the heart of production

506
00:33:52,003 --> 00:33:53,244
on this game, I was actually working

507
00:33:53,284 --> 00:33:54,845
on five different projects at a time.

508
00:33:55,485 --> 00:33:58,307
I worked too hard, and I ended up in the hospital

509
00:33:58,367 --> 00:33:59,367
because I worked too hard.

510
00:34:00,628 --> 00:34:05,371
And I had to hire help, which I'll get to in just a moment.

511
00:34:07,018 --> 00:34:12,164
Some of my other challenges is that being an indie game,

512
00:34:12,585 --> 00:34:16,390
there's not a very large budget for the music.

513
00:34:17,144 --> 00:34:18,645
Let alone for live players.

514
00:34:19,106 --> 00:34:24,130
And I knew that there was going to be mostly samples in the score, but I also knew that

515
00:34:24,451 --> 00:34:29,656
just recording a few live instruments completely brings tracks to life.

516
00:34:30,156 --> 00:34:31,938
So I can't recommend it enough.

517
00:34:31,998 --> 00:34:37,744
If you've got a track that is almost all samples, just find one instrument that you can record

518
00:34:37,804 --> 00:34:40,587
live and it just brings so much life to the track.

519
00:34:41,207 --> 00:34:44,029
So I knew I wanted banjo and fretless bass,

520
00:34:44,069 --> 00:34:45,649
which I'd never heard in a game score,

521
00:34:45,769 --> 00:34:47,030
and a couple other things.

522
00:34:47,050 --> 00:34:49,191
I knew I had male and female vocalists

523
00:34:49,291 --> 00:34:53,813
for the front main title screen and a brass section.

524
00:34:55,074 --> 00:34:57,035
Where was I going to find players to do this?

525
00:34:58,515 --> 00:35:00,436
Is everybody familiar with the Materia Collective?

526
00:35:01,437 --> 00:35:01,577
No?

527
00:35:01,817 --> 00:35:01,997
Great.

528
00:35:02,337 --> 00:35:03,638
So let me introduce you to them.

529
00:35:04,718 --> 00:35:09,841
The Materia Collective is a video game music fan community.

530
00:35:10,485 --> 00:35:17,491
They are a group of musicians, not unlike the Overclock Remix community, who do cover

531
00:35:17,511 --> 00:35:22,835
versions of music, but they are also a record label.

532
00:35:24,397 --> 00:35:26,378
And they put out their own albums.

533
00:35:26,418 --> 00:35:34,325
And because of this, they are getting used to the idea of producing top-notch, high-quality

534
00:35:34,385 --> 00:35:34,705
music.

535
00:35:36,750 --> 00:35:38,831
But they are still a fan community.

536
00:35:38,891 --> 00:35:41,732
So I knew that these were going to be young players who

537
00:35:41,772 --> 00:35:44,994
were really good, liked game music, were familiar with it,

538
00:35:45,054 --> 00:35:47,514
would jump at the chance to work on an actual game.

539
00:35:48,895 --> 00:35:50,576
But their experience level was going

540
00:35:50,596 --> 00:35:51,716
to fit the budget that I had.

541
00:35:53,317 --> 00:35:55,878
So the first bit of help I hired.

542
00:35:57,433 --> 00:35:59,155
was Francesco Del Pia.

543
00:35:59,836 --> 00:36:03,400
He was what I'm going to call a technical music

544
00:36:03,440 --> 00:36:07,124
designer in Vancouver, which was great,

545
00:36:07,224 --> 00:36:09,166
because now he was in the same time zone as me.

546
00:36:09,227 --> 00:36:10,608
So we could just chat throughout the day.

547
00:36:10,648 --> 00:36:12,650
And I didn't have to wait up until like 3 in the morning

548
00:36:12,691 --> 00:36:14,653
to talk to him about iteration.

549
00:36:16,764 --> 00:36:20,426
And he helped me out designing all the interactive music

550
00:36:20,486 --> 00:36:22,628
and trying to stitch together pieces on the fly

551
00:36:23,308 --> 00:36:25,590
and figuring out whether layers would work better

552
00:36:25,650 --> 00:36:26,971
or chunks stitched together.

553
00:36:27,831 --> 00:36:28,632
He was great at that.

554
00:36:28,832 --> 00:36:30,954
Then, after I hired Francesco,

555
00:36:31,554 --> 00:36:34,176
I seemingly hired every musician in North America

556
00:36:34,876 --> 00:36:40,080
to sing on the track or to play banjo for me

557
00:36:40,220 --> 00:36:41,861
or ocarina or harmonica

558
00:36:42,742 --> 00:36:44,323
and a vocalist down in Chile.

559
00:36:45,924 --> 00:36:51,847
Now, the big challenge with this is that I needed to make it sound like everybody was

560
00:36:51,887 --> 00:36:53,488
recorded in the same studio.

561
00:36:53,508 --> 00:36:59,252
I needed to make sure that everything was homogenous when in reality I'm getting who

562
00:36:59,312 --> 00:37:02,093
knows what from people across the globe.

563
00:37:02,814 --> 00:37:06,076
And I needed to make sure they had the right delivery specs

564
00:37:06,096 --> 00:37:06,596
for everything.

565
00:37:06,917 --> 00:37:09,298
Everything needed to be up to the quality level, that when I

566
00:37:09,358 --> 00:37:11,660
put everything together, it took some shaping, and it took

567
00:37:11,720 --> 00:37:14,002
some mixing and some tweaking.

568
00:37:14,522 --> 00:37:17,124
But I managed to make it all sound very homogenous.

569
00:37:19,746 --> 00:37:19,946
Tom.

570
00:37:20,787 --> 00:37:22,108
So, underwear.

571
00:37:24,690 --> 00:37:24,850
Yeah.

572
00:37:25,712 --> 00:37:29,712
In the age of Unity and Unreal, it would be crazy to build your own engine from scratch,

573
00:37:29,972 --> 00:37:31,733
and that's exactly what the team did.

574
00:37:32,193 --> 00:37:36,874
So Underwear is the name of the purpose-built engine that powers Yoku's Island Express.

575
00:37:37,614 --> 00:37:41,795
So it's got a live editor mode, so you can switch backwards and forwards between the

576
00:37:41,835 --> 00:37:44,875
game and the editor and set up the audio really easily.

577
00:37:44,895 --> 00:37:48,816
It meant a really fast iteration loop, which was awesome.

578
00:37:49,256 --> 00:37:51,016
And in my experience, fast iteration

579
00:37:51,777 --> 00:37:56,640
is the same as greater quality, because you're spending more time on getting those assets

580
00:37:56,680 --> 00:37:57,881
sounding great in context.

581
00:37:58,542 --> 00:38:02,344
And it had the visual editor that looked a lot like this, so I could easily see where

582
00:38:02,364 --> 00:38:04,286
I needed to hook the sounds into.

583
00:38:04,946 --> 00:38:06,027
Made it very straightforward.

584
00:38:06,527 --> 00:38:10,450
Although you did have some situations that looked more like this.

585
00:38:10,470 --> 00:38:13,472
I don't really know what's going on there, but the sound works.

586
00:38:13,933 --> 00:38:16,234
So there you go.

587
00:38:16,455 --> 00:38:20,858
And we had a few key technical issues on the project, as it's a physics-based game.

588
00:38:21,737 --> 00:38:23,897
Primarily, especially when you had multiple,

589
00:38:24,357 --> 00:38:25,618
is that there were too many loops.

590
00:38:25,678 --> 00:38:29,578
In fact, we had so many loops that all the sound cut out

591
00:38:29,618 --> 00:38:31,159
from the game at times.

592
00:38:31,919 --> 00:38:36,380
So we came up with a solution using the wise feature

593
00:38:36,500 --> 00:38:39,781
of multi-sounds, where you have a single sound that's

594
00:38:40,021 --> 00:38:42,701
sort of spread over multiple locations,

595
00:38:42,761 --> 00:38:44,162
and it takes the average pan.

596
00:38:44,362 --> 00:38:47,062
And well, actually, that created some other problems.

597
00:38:47,142 --> 00:38:49,923
But I'll take those problems over all the sound cutting out.

598
00:38:49,983 --> 00:38:51,063
So, you know.

599
00:38:52,476 --> 00:38:59,422
We also had an open world zoomable map, which was pretty interesting because a lot of the

600
00:38:59,482 --> 00:39:04,507
way that the sound is designed to work in Wwise is based on a 3D principle.

601
00:39:04,607 --> 00:39:09,832
So when you can be sort of zoomed in on one game area or zoomed out looking at the whole

602
00:39:09,872 --> 00:39:10,252
thing or...

603
00:39:10,692 --> 00:39:18,259
Part way in between, it made it a bit challenging to set up the attenuations in a sensible way and figure out what sounds actually needed to be playing.

604
00:39:18,960 --> 00:39:22,463
So the way we figured that out was something we called the listener rectangle.

605
00:39:22,823 --> 00:39:23,504
And here's a picture.

606
00:39:24,444 --> 00:39:27,767
So this is in editor mode. We can see the listener rectangle.

607
00:39:27,787 --> 00:39:30,410
You've got an inner and an outer rectangle.

608
00:39:31,130 --> 00:39:36,115
And in between the inner and the outer is a range of 0 to 1000.

609
00:39:38,016 --> 00:39:40,818
And that defined the volume and the pan.

610
00:39:41,219 --> 00:39:44,201
And inside the rectangle, it was maximum volume and center pan,

611
00:39:44,801 --> 00:39:47,083
which was great because it was on screen space.

612
00:39:47,123 --> 00:39:49,045
So however zoomed out or zoomed in you were,

613
00:39:49,385 --> 00:39:51,307
it would choose the appropriate sounds to be playing

614
00:39:51,387 --> 00:39:52,968
and set the volumes appropriately.

615
00:39:53,889 --> 00:39:57,351
And this view gave us a view of all the RTPCs

616
00:39:57,391 --> 00:39:58,312
and the sounds playing.

617
00:39:58,412 --> 00:40:00,874
So this is a really helpful debug view.

618
00:40:02,996 --> 00:40:07,739
And I thought I'd give you a few key technical questions that I asked myself.

619
00:40:07,799 --> 00:40:13,804
So when you're planning your 2D open world Metroidvania pinball game with a Cthulian Elder God problem,

620
00:40:13,844 --> 00:40:15,185
you can ask yourself these questions.

621
00:40:16,845 --> 00:40:18,926
How fast is the iteration speed?

622
00:40:19,086 --> 00:40:21,787
Like I said, iteration speed directly correlates

623
00:40:22,007 --> 00:40:25,249
with the quality, so that's important.

624
00:40:25,969 --> 00:40:28,670
How is your tech gonna work with thousands of assets?

625
00:40:28,711 --> 00:40:30,351
It's all very well if it works with one or two

626
00:40:30,391 --> 00:40:32,212
for your test cases, but when you scale up,

627
00:40:32,732 --> 00:40:34,473
what kind of problems are you gonna see?

628
00:40:36,049 --> 00:40:38,191
How is your tech going to affect asset creation?

629
00:40:38,251 --> 00:40:40,133
So you might come up with a new way of doing things,

630
00:40:40,933 --> 00:40:42,295
and that might require your assets

631
00:40:42,315 --> 00:40:43,356
to be made in a different way.

632
00:40:43,776 --> 00:40:45,458
So you need to have this figured out early

633
00:40:45,898 --> 00:40:47,740
so that you can make all the assets in the same way.

634
00:40:49,081 --> 00:40:50,242
How easy is it to debug?

635
00:40:51,083 --> 00:40:53,205
So having great debug tools like we did

636
00:40:53,566 --> 00:40:56,369
is really going to make closing the project down a lot easier

637
00:40:56,389 --> 00:40:58,551
and a lot more straightforward and a lot less stressful.

638
00:40:59,816 --> 00:41:02,359
But then what risks is your tech going to introduce,

639
00:41:02,619 --> 00:41:04,701
and how comfortable is the team with those risks?

640
00:41:05,322 --> 00:41:06,583
So that's worth considering.

641
00:41:07,664 --> 00:41:10,287
And then how flexible is your tech for special cases?

642
00:41:10,307 --> 00:41:11,829
There's always going to be places where

643
00:41:12,249 --> 00:41:13,510
the tech doesn't really work.

644
00:41:13,550 --> 00:41:16,734
So for us, that was boss battles or little scripted sequences

645
00:41:16,774 --> 00:41:19,436
that we kind of had to work into our tech.

646
00:41:20,609 --> 00:41:22,870
And then lastly, what's the bang for buck?

647
00:41:23,490 --> 00:41:26,772
So you could come up with the best audio system ever,

648
00:41:26,832 --> 00:41:28,452
the most nuanced and interesting,

649
00:41:28,552 --> 00:41:30,773
but if your average user isn't going to notice it,

650
00:41:31,434 --> 00:41:33,635
what's the point in spending your time and resources on it?

651
00:41:35,876 --> 00:41:42,638
So when we sat down to begin the process of making the music

652
00:41:42,698 --> 00:41:46,840
tech, Tom said to me, just make it good enough for a GDC talk.

653
00:41:49,341 --> 00:41:49,521
And

654
00:41:51,125 --> 00:41:54,208
I didn't, unfortunately, but here we are.

655
00:41:55,529 --> 00:42:01,495
Reason is that too many simultaneous layers and streams totally nuked the engine.

656
00:42:04,337 --> 00:42:14,286
And towards Tom's point of does it have bang for its buck, the team decided that all this

657
00:42:14,446 --> 00:42:15,828
nuanced, interactive...

658
00:42:17,129 --> 00:42:21,533
mixing on the fly and changing out instruments and whatnot,

659
00:42:22,413 --> 00:42:24,795
they didn't notice it and they were working with it

660
00:42:25,696 --> 00:42:29,440
on a day-to-day basis, and it was nuking all of the game.

661
00:42:30,561 --> 00:42:32,683
So, in the end.

662
00:42:34,797 --> 00:42:38,719
It ended up music is just based on macro level locations.

663
00:42:40,179 --> 00:42:42,741
There's a snow area.

664
00:42:42,941 --> 00:42:44,481
It has two pieces of snow music.

665
00:42:45,242 --> 00:42:46,062
There are caves.

666
00:42:46,102 --> 00:42:47,483
They have two pieces of cave music.

667
00:42:48,563 --> 00:42:50,084
It's way more basic than I wanted,

668
00:42:51,525 --> 00:42:54,706
but it is how it worked out.

669
00:42:55,527 --> 00:42:57,688
So how do I spin that as positive?

670
00:42:58,448 --> 00:43:02,570
Because when you are working on an indie title.

671
00:43:03,219 --> 00:43:10,125
As opposed to a AAA title, you don't have the infrastructure that you get from a AAA

672
00:43:10,185 --> 00:43:11,145
development studio.

673
00:43:11,786 --> 00:43:17,051
So if you're going to go out and try and promote the game, you're going to have to hire a

674
00:43:19,412 --> 00:43:23,114
PR company, or you're going to have to do a lot of legwork yourself trying to line up

675
00:43:23,154 --> 00:43:26,476
interviews with podcasts and websites.

676
00:43:27,757 --> 00:43:35,782
So the PR hook that I decided to go with was, oh, music's handled like a throwback shoutout

677
00:43:35,862 --> 00:43:38,403
to the classic NES games I grew up loving.

678
00:43:39,767 --> 00:43:44,631
Um, which is true, it functions that way, but it's not the goal I set out to do.

679
00:43:45,412 --> 00:43:52,918
Um, but it sounded like a positive, and I could instead, um, hang my hat on the creative

680
00:43:52,958 --> 00:43:57,942
element of the score, the dichotomy of opposites thing that I had worked so hard at with the

681
00:43:58,143 --> 00:43:58,943
music's production.

682
00:43:59,864 --> 00:44:05,769
Um, and I could let go, uh, the ability to talk about the music tech.

683
00:44:08,071 --> 00:44:08,191
So.

684
00:44:09,238 --> 00:44:15,180
All right, well, in summary, build your relationships

685
00:44:15,541 --> 00:44:18,202
and gain understanding before talking money

686
00:44:18,382 --> 00:44:19,322
with new developers.

687
00:44:19,702 --> 00:44:22,704
Relationships really are what this business is all about.

688
00:44:23,844 --> 00:44:26,205
Take all of your risks in pre-production

689
00:44:26,625 --> 00:44:28,966
and have all your systems working in pre-production.

690
00:44:28,986 --> 00:44:32,528
It's really going to make production that much easier.

691
00:44:32,748 --> 00:44:34,048
Do all your panicking early.

692
00:44:35,471 --> 00:44:39,675
Maintain regular communication with the team. It really is the lifeblood of the project.

693
00:44:40,436 --> 00:44:45,682
There was some times when we got a bit crunchy where that failed and it caused us loads of problems.

694
00:44:45,802 --> 00:44:47,043
Always causes problems.

695
00:44:48,184 --> 00:44:50,386
Live instruments and field recording are awesome. Do that.

696
00:44:54,070 --> 00:44:57,151
Indie projects often don't have the infrastructure of AAA.

697
00:44:57,271 --> 00:45:01,412
So often you don't have QA, PR, or marketing,

698
00:45:01,452 --> 00:45:03,432
though we did from Team17, and they were awesome.

699
00:45:04,573 --> 00:45:06,233
But other projects haven't had that.

700
00:45:07,233 --> 00:45:08,594
So you have to plan for that.

701
00:45:08,994 --> 00:45:11,154
And then you have no institutional limitations.

702
00:45:11,174 --> 00:45:12,574
So often you've got no NDA, which

703
00:45:12,614 --> 00:45:14,195
means we could tweet about it and talk about it.

704
00:45:14,455 --> 00:45:15,995
That was pretty amazing, the ability

705
00:45:16,015 --> 00:45:20,056
to just screenshot Saturday anything I was working on.

706
00:45:21,176 --> 00:45:22,156
That never happens in AAA.

707
00:45:22,802 --> 00:45:26,065
Yeah, it meant we could come to GDC and actually tell people what we were doing, which is great.

708
00:45:27,426 --> 00:45:29,027
And that's it. Thank you.

709
00:45:29,267 --> 00:45:29,588
Thank you.

